tors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOngoing debates about the “return of religion” have paid little attention to the orgiastic and enthusiastic qualities of religiosity, despite a significant increase in the use of techniques of trance and possession around the globe. Likewise, research on religion and media has neglected the fact that historically the rise of mediumship and spirit possession was closely linked to the development of new media of communication.This innovative volume brings together a wide range of ethnographic studies on local spiritual and media practices. Recognizing that processes of globalization are shaped by mass mediation, the volume raises questions such as: How are media like photography, cinema, video, the telephone, or television integrated in seances and healing rituals? How do spirit mediums connect with these media? Why are certain technical media shunned in these contexts?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aChanneling (Spiritualism)vCongresses. 0aGlobalizationvCongresses. 0aMass media and anthropologyvCongresses. 0aTechnologyvCongresses. 4aAnthropology. 4aCinema & Media Studies. 4aReligion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh  acine-trance.  aecstatic practices.  amedia / new media.  amedia anthropology.  amedia.  amediumship.  areligion studies.  areligion.  aspirit possession.  aspirituality.  atrance.1 aBehrend, Heike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehrend, Heike, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBöhme, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDreschke, Anja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuzy, Lidia, econtr